author: The Virginian-Pilot
title: Roundup | Wethington leads King's Fork to another big win
text:
No. 9 King's Fork 39, Great Bridge 9 Deshaun Wethington rushed for 289 yards and five touchdowns Monday night as the Bulldogs (4-1) cruised to a second straight lopsided victory.
Wethington, a senior, surged into fourth on South Hampton Roads' regular-season career rushing list with 4,207 yards. Wethington averaged 19.3 yards on his 15 attempts and rushed for TDs of 7, 2, 52, 18 and 15 yards. He has 769 yards this season despite missing the season opener with an injury.
Great Bridge (0-5) managed just 108 total yards and punted five times.
First Colonial 27, Tallwood 6
The Patriots limited Tallwood to 13 first-half yards and scored 27 points after the break to win for the third time in four games.
First Colonial (3-3) finished with 243 total yards, including 166 on the ground.
Devonta Hill scored the Patriots' first points when he hopped on a blocked punt by Sean Williams, and Rayshawn Steverson rushed for 76 yards and a TD.
Tallwood fell to 2-4.
Key stats: T-Zuri Cason 16-77 rushing; Adrion Wilson 6-10-0, 74 yards, TD passing; Brendan Scott 2-23, TD receiving; FC-Steverson 20-76, TD rushing; Jamaal Lopes 4-62 rushing; Scotty Watson 5-9-1, 77 yards, TD passing; 6-21, TD rushing; Dauvieh Bradshaw 2-42, TD receiving.
He said it: "I hadn't seen the team since Thursday, so I was a little concerned about how the guys would come out and play tonight. But once we got started we were able to keep everything rolling from there." - Sam Scarborough, First Colonial coach.
- Reported by Jamaar Hawkins
No. 1 Ocean Lakes 49, Kempsville 6
Khalan Laborn sprinted for 232 yards and five touchdowns - including a 99-yarder - to lead the Dolphins (5-0) in their final game without head coach Chris Scott.
Scott is scheduled to return to practice today after serving a five-game suspension after the program violated the Virginia High School League's recruiting rule.
Kempsville fell to 0-6, but accounted itself well against the nationally ranked Dolphins. The Chiefs ran off 49 plays to Ocean Lakes' 28 and had an 11-8 advantage in first downs. But they were no match for the big-play fireworks of Laborn.
He carried just nine times, all in the first half.
Key stats: OL-Laborn 9-232, 5 TDs rushing; K-Brad Lee 20-52, TD rushing; Jackson Droll 10-33 rushing.
- Reported by John Acree
Lakeland 30, Deep Creek 13
Tyquan Holloman's 67-yard touchdown pass to Derrick Grant with 5:03 left gave the Cavaliers a 16-0 lead on their way to a second consecutive victory.
Grant's TD started a flurry of scoring plays in a game that was marred by foul weather and poor field conditions. The teams combined for six fumbles, and the Hornets amassed 118 penalty yards to Lakeland's 70.
The teams combined for 34 fourth-quarter points, including Damontra Milteer's 29-yard fumble return for Lakeland and Kimani Kellam's 65-yard TD run for Deep Creek in the final minute.
Deep Creek's Riley Dellinger booted a 63-yard punt to set a school record, beating Joe Verdi's 62-yarder in 1990.
Key stats: DC-Kellam 3-67, TD rushing; L-Milteer 11-33 rushing; Holloman 6-12-0, 115 yards, TD passing.
- Reported by John Streit
